snippet.textDisplay:
Tbh, im upset that fed didnt get that first set cuz I feel there is more of that weakness of playing big points poorly showing up.

But realistically, the way he was moving, and the super risky play style he was forced into to cover his movement issues, he would have lost in 4 sets if he won the first.

And even IF he magically won this match, what chance really would he have at winning vs thiem in the finals?

In order to win vs djokovic fed would have had to push himself, and them vs thiem still more. Pushing yourself on a injury at his age is a good way to make it a serious injury and end his career.

Take a rest roger. Try your best to recover and build up your conditioning, and lets try again next slam.

snippet.textDisplay: I am a huge Roger fan, but will admit that at this point in his career, he will probably never win another slam.  Novak is just too good, and Roger’s best days are behind him.  I would not say that it is time for Roger to retire, as he still enjoys playing, and still seems to make it to the semi finals frequently, and is not embarrassing himself. While I admire Novak’s skill as a player, I just do not care for him.  It began with his imitating other great players when he was just breaking onto the tennis scene - I think it showed that he had no respect for the people he was imitating.  I also do not like his chest beating when he wins a great point, or his grass-eating at Wimbledon. He is an amazing player, and I hope I can grow to like him.

snippet.textDisplay: This is what happens when Federer plays someone who actually has a brain on court, and not a pretender like Millman or Sandgren. Sandgren couldn't even beat an injured Fed who was actually BETTER than Fed in all but 2 stat categories, I believe. It's not often you see Federer have 30+ less winners, more errors, less first serve points percentage, less first serve points won by percentage, less total points won, saved fewer break points, and served up only 5 aces, and still somehow win. Heck, Barty had more aces in the entire first set of her semifinal than Federer had in his entire 5 set match. Forget those stats, how many times has Federer won less points at net than his opponent? That was the worst non-clay match I can ever recall Federer playing since the day he first became world #1, and he's lost matches where he played a hell of a lot better, including the 2005 AO semi vs. Safin. This is also the first tournament where Federer looked his age. He's defied the rules of the physical body for so long, and I don't think he should play the clay season. He's not going to win anything on clay and it'd be very rough to play clay, grass, and hard in the span of a month (with Olympics only taking place two weeks after Wimbledon)

snippet.textDisplay: Fed's first serve is better than Djoko's and his serve return was amazingly as good as Djoko's.   But he can rely on big first serves to win because there'll be times they don't fall in or Djoko is able to hit a good return.  So in the end rallies usually decide the game.  Without arguing whether or not Fed was slowed down by some injury (because only he knows deep down inside), Djoko was clearly better in rallies.  Winner/Unforced error stats are not enough to show it.  A stat that also should be shown is forced errors.  Djoko is a careful player.  He usually doesn't risk a shot for a winner but rather forces you into a difficult shot so you can make an error.  This stat is not shown and that's why if you look at the other stats you'd ask how did he win the match.   Many times in this match Djoko hit heavy balls that forced Fed into making errors.  That is one of Djoko's strengths.  It's not a "beautiful" thing like when Fed hits those inside-out forehand winners.  That's why more people like Fed and think Djoko's game is boring.  But in the end winning is what matters.
snippet.textOriginal: Fed's first serve is better than Djoko's and his serve return was amazingly as good as Djoko's.   But he can rely on big first serves to win because there'll be times they don't fall in or Djoko is able to hit a good return.  So in the end rallies usually decide the game.  Without arguing whether or not Fed was slowed down by some injury (because only he knows deep down inside), Djoko was clearly better in rallies.  Winner/Unforced error stats are not enough to show it.  A stat that also should be shown is forced errors.  Djoko is a careful player.  He usually doesn't risk a shot for a winner but rather forces you into a difficult shot so you can make an error.
